Some Threat Modeling Methods:

STRIDE, a Microsoft framework that categorizes threats into spoofing, tampering, repudiation, information disclosure, denial of service, and elevation of privilege

PASTA, a risk centric seven stage methodology that aligns business objectives with technical requirements to model and prioritize threats

LINDDUN, a privacy focused threat modeling framework addressing threats like likability, identifiability, non repudiation, detectability, disclosure, unawareness, and non compliance

Attack Trees, a hierarchical diagram technique that models how an attacker could achieve a specific goal through different paths

PnG (process for attack simulation and threat analysis), a quantitative method using simulation to evaluate potential attack paths and impacts

Trike, a security auditing framework that uses threat modeling to define system requirements and generate risk based security metrics

VAST (visual, agile, and simple threat), a scalable threat modeling approach that integrates with DevOps pipelines to support both application and operational threat analysis



