Inherent, Residual, and Current Risk:

risk is inevitable. it is inherent in anything an organization undertakes

risk practitioners should understand risk, assess and respond to risk outside of risk appetite

practitioners should also understand the difference between inherent, residual, and current risk














Inherent Risk:

the risk level or exposure without considering the actions a company has taken or might take

the risk is present in any chosen course of action that I not specifically avoided








Residual Risk: 

the remaining risk after management has implemented a risk response

calculated by subtracting the effectiveness of the risk response from inherent risk

residual risk is what risk appetite is based upon










Current Risk:

residual risk is more in line with predictive perspective

current risk can tend to confuse those that aren't following a risk management framework

current risk = current "point in time" risk associated with an asset where actions taken and actions pending are considered














Mitigation, Transference, Avoidance Response:

the goal of risk response is to bring risk into alignment with the business risk appetite and tolerance

risk assessment report and risk register document the risk identified and analyzed/assessed

the recommendations made are guidelines

there are four responses; acceptance, mitigation, transfer and avoid











Mitigation of Risk:

actions taken to reduce the impact of risk

typically accomplished by installing controls 

the goal is to reduce risk to an acceptable level, not to eliminate it

generally, less expensive than avoidance and transference










Transferring Risk:

reduces loss by having another organization handle the impact

commonly done through third party insurance

doesn't mean the organization wont feel the impact

stakeholders rarely feel that the organization is not to blame












Avoidance of Risk:

exiting the activities or conditions that give risk to risk

current exposure is deemed unacceptable by senior management

chosen when it is impossible to mitigate or transfer 

impact here is typically loss of opportunity











Risk Acceptance:

acceptance is a conscious decision by senior management

recognizes the existence and impact of a risk

sometimes referred to as "self-insurance"

typically uses management reserves as a backup in case the risk event occurs

risk falls within the company's risk appetite generally will be accepted

management might also choose acceptance if risk is within tolerance

risk that is accepted must be done so formally

informal risk acceptance is called risk ignorance

accepting risk at the onset deals with inherent risk

accepting risk after mitigation deals with residual risk

risk acceptance is not a one-time process

regular reviews need to take place to make sure risk remains within risk appetite or tolerances















