Using Key Control Indicators (KCIs):

certain indicators show the control effectiveness to the team

the indicator should quantify how well a specific control is working

the goal of a KCI is to track performance of control actions relative to tolerances

KCI examples include phishing emails blocked or not blocked, admins with right to both test and production environments, and unsolicited prompts for second-factor authentication












Key Control Indicators:

each KCI has its own tolerances based on the asset it protects

KCIs are correlated with the risk they are meant to mitigate

this correlation also means that all KCIs are themselves risk indicators










