Enterprise Architecture Categories:

documentation, the recorded descriptions, models, and artifacts that capture the structure, components, and relationships within an enterprise

notation, the standardized symbols, diagrams, and languages used to represent enterprise architecture elements consistently

process, the methods and workflows followed to develop, manage, and maintain enterprise architecture across its lifecycle

organization, the governance structures, roles, and responsibilities that define how enterprise architecture is managed within the business











Architecture Frameworks:

TOGAF, The Open Group Architecture Framework, a comprehensive methodology and set of tools for designing, planning, implementing, and governing enterprise architectures

Zachman Framework, a taxonomy that organizes enterprise architecture artifacts into a matrix based on perspectives (who, what, where, why, how) and levels of detail

DODAF, The Department of Defense Architecture Framework, used by the U.S. DoD to ensure systems architecture aligns with military operations and standards

FEAF, The Federal Enterprise Architecture Framework, a U.S. government framework designed to align business processes and IT across federal agencies

SABSA, The Sherwood Applied Business Security Architecture, a framework focused on developing risk-driven enterprise security architectures













